        scenarios: [
          { scenario: "A smart thermostat learns your schedule and automatically adjusts temperature. One morning it drops the heat to 60\u00b0F because it predicted you left for work \u2014 but you're home sick. The only way to override is through a phone app buried 3 menus deep. You're shivering in bed trying to navigate tiny buttons.", question: "Using HCI concepts from the Boeing 737 MAX case study, analyze what went wrong in this interaction. Identify the parallels to MCAS.", answer: "This mirrors the MCAS pattern: the system predicts behavior, acts before confirmation, and minimizes the visible interface. Like MCAS, the thermostat creates an authority inversion \u2014 it decides first, the human reacts later. The override is buried (poor recoverability), the system's intent isn't visible (no display showing 'I think you left'), and cognitive load is high (sick person navigating complex menus). The interface gap: you see effects (cold house) but not system intent (schedule prediction). Fix: show the prediction on the device ('Away mode \u2014 tap to stay'), provide a physical override button, and require confirmation before acting on predictions.", concepts: ["authority inversion", "interface gap", "recoverability", "system transparency", "automation vs interface"] },
          { scenario: "A hospital deploys a new electronic health record system. Nurses report that entering a single patient's vitals now takes 47 clicks across 6 screens, compared to 12 fields on the old paper form. Error rates have tripled, and nurses are spending more time on data entry than patient care. The vendor says nurses need 'more training.'", question: "Using HCI principles, explain why 'more training' is not the right diagnosis. What usability goals are being violated?", answer: "This is a classic 'human error is a red flag' situation. HCI says: when users consistently struggle, the problem is the design, not the user. The vendor's response mirrors blaming pilots for MCAS failures. Usability goals violated: Efficiency (47 clicks vs 12 fields \u2014 dramatically worse), Learnability (6 screens for one task is unnecessarily complex), Errors (tripled error rate = design problem), Satisfaction (nurses frustrated, spending time on system instead of patients). The system fails the core HCI question: can users act safely and effectively under real conditions? Training cannot compensate for a fundamentally inefficient interface.", concepts: ["human error as design signal", "five usability goals", "efficiency", "cognitive load", "training vs design"] },
          { scenario: "A ride-sharing app shows a map with your driver approaching, an estimated arrival time, the driver's name and photo, car make/model/color, and license plate. Compare this to calling a traditional taxi where you're told 'a car will arrive soon.'", question: "Analyze both experiences using HCI concepts of system transparency, legibility, and control. Why does one feel better than the other?", answer: "The ride-sharing app makes automation visible: you can see the system's state (driver location), predict its behavior (ETA with live updates), and verify it (car details for identification). This is automation that assists effectively \u2014 goals visible, limits legible, behavior predictable. The taxi call is like MCAS: the system is acting (dispatching a car) but provides no visibility into its state. You can't see where the car is, when it'll arrive, or even confirm it's coming. There's no recoverability (if it's late, you can only call again). The ride-sharing app answers HCI's repeating question: Who understands what the system is doing? You do, in real-time. The taxi call leaves you in the dark.", concepts: ["system transparency", "legibility", "predictability", "recoverability", "automation visibility"] },
          { scenario: "A university's course registration system crashes every semester during enrollment. Students have learned workarounds: opening 5 browser tabs, refreshing constantly, memorizing course numbers to type faster. The registrar says the system 'works fine' because everyone eventually gets registered.", question: "Using the distinction between usability and user experience, explain why the registrar is wrong. What are users actually experiencing?", answer: "The registrar confuses task completion with usability and UX. Yes, students eventually register (task completion) \u2014 but the usability goals are all failing: Learnability (students need workarounds), Efficiency (multiple tabs, constant refreshing), Errors (system crashes), Satisfaction (extremely stressful). The UX is terrible: emotions before (anxiety, dread), during (frustration, panic), and after (relief, not satisfaction). The three UX factors: the system (crashes), the user (stressed, time-pressured), the context (high-stakes limited enrollment). Users developing workarounds is a design signal, not proof that the system works. Human-centered design would solve the root problem (server capacity, queue system) not the symptom.", concepts: ["usability vs UX", "five usability goals", "three UX factors", "human-centered design", "root cause vs symptom"] },
          { scenario: "A self-checkout machine at a grocery store has a screen that says 'Place item in bagging area' after every scan. If you don't place it fast enough, it locks up and displays 'Unexpected item in bagging area \u2014 wait for assistance.' A line of frustrated customers forms behind you while you wait for an employee.", question: "Analyze this as an HCI failure. What interface design principles are violated, and how would you redesign the interaction?", answer: "The system demands specific behavior without explaining why, creating an interface gap. It punishes normal human variation in timing (cognitive load is already high when bagging). The error message is cryptic ('unexpected item' when you haven't done anything unexpected) \u2014 violating clarity. The lockout removes control entirely, violating recoverability. Redesign: increase the timing tolerance (design for human variation, not robotic precision), show a clear progress indicator ('Scan next item or tap Done'), make the weight-check passive rather than blocking, provide a simple 'Skip' button for the weight check that flags for later review rather than locking the entire system. The interface should work with cognitive limits, not against them.", concepts: ["interface gap", "recoverability", "control", "cognitive load", "designing for human variation"] },
        ],
